# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: envelope-encryption-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] The expression *full disk encryption (FDE)* (or *whole disk encryption*) signifies that everything on the disk is encrypted, barring the master boot record (MBR), or similar area of a bootable disk, with code that starts the operating system loading sequence.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Some hardware-based full disk encryption systems can truly encrypt an entire boot disk, including the MBR.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] With transparent encryption, the files are accessible immediately after the key is provided, and the entire volume is typically mounted as if it were a physical drive, making the files just as accessible as any unencrypted ones.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] No data stored on an encrypted volume can be read (decrypted) without using the correct password/keyfile(s) or correct encryption keys.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] The entire file system within the volume is encrypted (including file names, folder names, file contents, and other meta-data).
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] To be transparent to the end-user, transparent encryption usually requires the use of device drivers to enable the encryption process.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Although administrator access rights are normally required to install such drivers, encrypted volumes can typically be used by normal users without these rights.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] In general, every method in which data is seamlessly encrypted on write and decrypted on read, in such a way that the user and/or application software remains unaware of the process, can be called transparent encryption.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Disk encryption does not replace file encryption in all situations.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Disk encryption is sometimes used in conjunction with filesystem-level encryption with the intention of providing a more secure implementation.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Since disk encryption generally uses the same key for encrypting the whole drive, all of the data can be decrypted when the system runs.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] However, some disk encryption solutions use multiple keys for encrypting different volumes.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] If an attacker gains access to the computer at run-time, the attacker has access to all files.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Conventional file and folder encryption instead allows different keys for different portions of the disk.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Thus an attacker cannot extract information from still-encrypted files and folders.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Unlike disk encryption, filesystem-level encryption does not typically encrypt filesystem metadata, such as the directory structure, file names, modification timestamps or sizes.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Trusted Platform Module (TPM) is a secure cryptoprocessor embedded in the motherboard that can be used to authenticate a hardware device.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Since each TPM chip is unique to a particular device, it is capable of performing platform authentication.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] It can be used to verify that the system seeking the access is the expected system.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] A limited number of disk encryption solutions have support for TPM.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] These implementations can wrap the decryption key using the TPM, thus tying the hard disk drive (HDD) to a particular device.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] If the HDD is removed from that particular device and placed in another, the decryption process will fail.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Recovery is possible with the decryption password or token.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] The TPM can impose a limit on decryption attempts per unit time, making brute-forcing harder.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] The TPM itself is intended to be impossible to duplicate, so that the brute-force limit is not trivially bypassed.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Although this has the advantage that the disk cannot be removed from the device, it might create a single point of failure in the encryption.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] For example, if something happens to the TPM or the motherboard, a user would not be able to access the data by connecting the hard drive to another computer, unless that user has a separate recovery key.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] There are multiple tools available in the market that allow for disk encryption.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] However, they vary greatly in features and security.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] They are divided into three main categories: software-based, hardware-based within the storage device, and hardware-based elsewhere (such as CPU or host bus adaptor).
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Hardware-based full disk encryption within the storage device are called self-encrypting drives and have no impact on performance whatsoever.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Furthermore, the media-encryption key never leaves the device itself and is therefore not available to any malware in the operating system.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] The Trusted Computing Group Opal Storage Specification provides industry accepted standardization for self-encrypting drives.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] External hardware is considerably faster than the software-based solutions, although CPU versions may still have a performance impact, and the media encryption keys are not as well protected.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] There are other (non-TCGA/OPAL based) self-encrypted drives (SED) that don't have the known vulnerabilities of the TCG/OPAL based drives (see section below).
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] They are Host/OS and BIOS independent and don't rely on the TPM module or the motherboard BIOS, and their Encryption Key never leaves the crypto-boundary of the drive.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] All solutions for the boot drive require a pre-boot authentication component which is available for all types of solutions from a number of vendors.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] It is important in all cases that the authentication credentials are usually a major potential weakness since the symmetric cryptography is usually strong.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Secure and safe recovery mechanisms are essential to the large-scale deployment of any disk encryption solutions in an enterprise.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] The solution must provide an easy but secure way to recover passwords (most importantly data) in case the user leaves the company without notice or forgets the password.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Challenge–response password recovery mechanism allows the password to be recovered in a secure manner.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] It is offered by a limited number of disk encryption solutions.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] No secret data is exchanged during the recovery process.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Does not require a network connection, i.e. it works for users that are at a remote location.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] An emergency recovery information (ERI) file provides an alternative for recovery if a challenge–response mechanism is unfeasible due to the cost of helpdesk operatives for small companies or implementation challenges.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Most full disk encryption schemes are vulnerable to a cold boot attack, whereby encryption keys can be stolen by cold-booting a machine already running an operating system, then dumping the contents of memory before the data disappears.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] The attack relies on the data remanence property of computer memory, whereby data bits can take up to several minutes to degrade after power has been removed.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Even a Trusted Platform Module (TPM) is not effective against the attack, as the operating system needs to hold the decryption keys in memory in order to access the disk.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Full disk encryption is also vulnerable when a computer is stolen when suspended.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] As wake-up does not involve a BIOS boot sequence, it typically does not ask for the FDE password.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Hibernation, in contrast goes via a BIOS boot sequence, and is safe.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] All software-based encryption systems are vulnerable to various side channel attacks such as acoustic cryptanalysis and hardware keyloggers.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] In contrast, self-encrypting drives are not vulnerable to these attacks since the hardware encryption key never leaves the disk controller.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Also, most full disk encryption schemes don't protect from data tampering (or silent data corruption, i.e. bitrot).
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] That means they only provide privacy, but not integrity.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Block cipher-based encryption modes used for full disk encryption are not authenticated encryption themselves because of concerns of the storage overhead needed for authentication tags.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] One of the ways to mitigate these concerns, is to use file systems with full data integrity checks via checksums (like Btrfs or ZFS) on top of full disk encryption.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Full disk encryption has several benefits compared to regular file or folder encryption, or encrypted vaults.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] With full disk encryption, the decision of which individual files to encrypt is not left up to users' discretion.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] This is important for situations in which users might not want or might forget to encrypt sensitive files.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Immediate data destruction, such as simply destroying the cryptographic keys (crypto-shredding), renders the contained data useless.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] However, if security towards future attacks is a concern, purging or physical destruction is advised.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] One issue to address in full disk encryption is that the blocks where the operating system is stored must be decrypted before the OS can boot, meaning that the key has to be available before there is a user interface to ask for a password.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Most full disk encryption solutions utilize pre-boot authentication by loading a small, highly secure operating system which is strictly locked down and hashed versus system variables to check for the integrity of the pre-boot kernel.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] Some implementations such as BitLocker Drive Encryption can make use of hardware such as a Trusted Platform Module to ensure the integrity of the boot environment, and thereby frustrate attacks that target the boot loader by replacing it with a modified version.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] This ensures that authentication can take place in a controlled environment without the possibility of a bootkit being used to subvert the pre-boot decryption.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] With a pre-boot authentication environment, the key used to encrypt the data is not decrypted until an external key is input into the system.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/disk-encryption] All these possibilities have varying degrees of security; however, most are better than an unencrypted disk.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] In cryptography, **encryption** (more specifically, encoding) is the process of transforming information in a way that, ideally, only authorized parties can decode.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] This process converts the original representation of the information, known as plaintext, into an alternative form known as ciphertext.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Despite its goal, encryption does not itself prevent interference but denies the intelligible content to a would-be interceptor.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] For technical reasons, an encryption scheme usually uses a pseudo-random encryption key generated by an algorithm.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] It is possible to decrypt the message without possessing the key but, for a well-designed encryption scheme, considerable computational resources and skills are required.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] An authorized recipient can easily decrypt the message with the key provided by the originator to recipients but not to unauthorized users.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Historically, various forms of encryption have been used to aid in cryptography.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Early encryption techniques were often used in military messaging.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Since then, new techniques have emerged and become commonplace in all areas of modern computing.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Modern encryption schemes use the concepts of public-key and symmetric-key.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Modern encryption techniques ensure security because modern computers are inefficient at cracking the encryption.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] One of the earliest forms of encryption is symbol replacement, which was first found in the tomb of Khnumhotep II, who lived in 1900 BC Egypt.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Symbol replacement encryption is "non-standard," which means that the symbols require a cipher or key to understand.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] This type of early encryption was used throughout Ancient Greece and Rome for military purposes.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] One of the most famous military encryption developments was the Caesar cipher, in which a plaintext letter is shifted a fixed number of positions along the alphabet to get the encoded letter.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] A message encoded with this type of encryption could be decoded with a fixed number on the Caesar cipher.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Around 800 AD, Arab mathematician al-Kindi developed the technique of frequency analysis – which was an attempt to crack ciphers systematically, including the Caesar cipher.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] This technique looked at the frequency of letters in the encrypted message to determine the appropriate shift: for example, the most common letter in English text is E and is therefore likely to be represented by the letter that appears most commonly in the ciphertext.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] This technique was rendered ineffective by the polyalphabetic cipher, described by al-Qalqashandi (1355–1418) and Leon Battista Alberti (in 1465), which varied the substitution alphabet as encryption proceeded in order to confound such analysis.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Around 1790, Thomas Jefferson theorized a cipher to encode and decode messages to provide a more secure way of military correspondence.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] The cipher, known today as the Wheel Cipher or the Jefferson Disk, although never actually built, was theorized as a spool that could jumble an English message up to 36 characters.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] The message could be decrypted by plugging in the jumbled message to a receiver with an identical cipher.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] A similar device to the Jefferson Disk, the M-94, was developed in 1917 independently by US Army Major Joseph Mauborne.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] This device was used in U.S. military communications until 1942.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] In World War II, the Axis powers used a more advanced version of the M-94 called the Enigma Machine.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] The Enigma Machine was more complex because unlike the Jefferson Wheel and the M-94, each day the jumble of letters switched to a completely new combination.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Each day's combination was only known by the Axis, so many thought the only way to break the code would be to try over 17,000 combinations within 24 hours.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] The Allies used computing power to severely limit the number of reasonable combinations they needed to check every day, leading to the breaking of the Enigma Machine.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Today, encryption is used in the transfer of communication over the Internet for security and commerce.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] As computing power continues to increase, computer encryption is constantly evolving to prevent eavesdropping attacks.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] One of the first "modern" cipher suites, DES, used a 56-bit key with 72,057,594,037,927,936 possibilities; it was cracked in 1999 by EFF's brute-force DES cracker, which required 22 hours and 15 minutes to do so.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Modern encryption standards often use stronger key sizes, such as AES (256-bit mode), TwoFish, ChaCha20-Poly1305, Serpent (configurable up to 512-bit).
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Cipher suites that use a 128-bit or higher key, like AES, cannot be brute-forced because the total number of keys is 3.4028237e+38 possibilities.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] The most likely option for cracking ciphers with large key sizes is to find vulnerabilities in the cipher itself, like inherent biases and backdoors or by exploiting physical side effects through Side-channel attacks.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] For example, RC4, a stream cipher, was cracked due to inherent biases and vulnerabilities in the cipher.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] In the context of cryptography, encryption serves as a mechanism to ensure confidentiality.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Since data may be visible on the Internet, sensitive information such as passwords and personal communication may be exposed to potential interceptors.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] The process of encrypting and decrypting messages involves keys.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] The two main types of keys in cryptographic systems are symmetric-key and public-key (also known as asymmetric-key).
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Many complex cryptographic algorithms often use simple modular arithmetic in their implementations.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] In symmetric-key schemes, the encryption and decryption keys are the same.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Communicating parties must have the same key in order to achieve secure communication.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] The German Enigma Machine used a new symmetric-key each day for encoding and decoding messages.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] In public-key cryptography schemes, the encryption key is published for anyone to use and encrypt messages.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] However, only the receiving party has access to the decryption key that enables messages to be read.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Public-key encryption was first described in a secret document in 1973; beforehand, all encryption schemes were symmetric-key (also called private-key).
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Although published subsequently, the work of Diffie and Hellman was published in a journal with a large readership, and the value of the methodology was explicitly described.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] The method became known as the Diffie-Hellman key exchange.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] RSA (Rivest–Shamir–Adleman) is another notable public-key cryptosystem.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Created in 1978, it is still used today for applications involving digital signatures.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Using number theory, the RSA algorithm selects two prime numbers, which help generate both the encryption and decryption keys.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] A publicly available public-key encryption application called Pretty Good Privacy (PGP) was written in 1991 by Phil Zimmermann, and distributed free of charge with source code.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] PGP was purchased by Symantec in 2010 and is regularly updated.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Encryption has long been used by militaries and governments to facilitate secret communication.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] It is now commonly used in protecting information within many kinds of civilian systems.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] For example, the Computer Security Institute reported that in 2007, 71% of companies surveyed used encryption for some of their data in transit, and 53% used encryption for some of their data in storage.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Encryption can be used to protect data "at rest", such as information stored on computers and storage devices (e.g.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] In recent years, there have been numerous reports of confidential data, such as customers' personal records, being exposed through loss or theft of laptops or backup drives; encrypting such files at rest helps protect them if physical security measures fail.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Digital rights management systems, which prevent unauthorized use or reproduction of copyrighted material and protect software against reverse engineering (see also copy protection), is another somewhat different example of using encryption on data at rest.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Encryption is also used to protect data in transit, for example data being transferred via networks (e.g. the Internet, e-commerce), mobile telephones, wireless microphones, wireless intercom systems, Bluetooth devices and bank automatic teller machines.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] There have been numerous reports of data in transit being intercepted in recent years.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Data should also be encrypted when transmitted across networks in order to protect against eavesdropping of network traffic by unauthorized users.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Encryption plays a central role in meeting regulatory requirements for the protection of sensitive data.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Under the HIPAA Security Rule, encryption of electronic protected health information (ePHI) is classified as an "addressable" implementation specification, meaning covered entities must implement it or document why an equivalent alternative measure is reasonable and appropriate.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Notably, the HIPAA Breach Notification Rule provides a safe harbor for encrypted data: breaches involving ePHI that has been encrypted in accordance with NIST standards are not considered reportable breaches.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] A proposed update to the HIPAA Security Rule (NPRM, December 2024) would make encryption of ePHI at rest and in transit a mandatory requirement, removing its current "addressable" status.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) requires encryption of cardholder data both in storage (Requirement 3) and during transmission over open public networks (Requirement 4), specifying the use of strong cryptographic algorithms.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Conventional methods for permanently deleting data from a storage device involve overwriting the device's whole content with zeros, ones, or other patterns – a process which can take a significant amount of time, depending on the capacity and the type of storage medium.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Cryptography offers a way of making the erasure almost instantaneous.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] An example implementation of this method can be found on iOS devices, where the cryptographic key is kept in a dedicated 'effaceable storage'.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Because the key is stored on the same device, this setup on its own does not offer full privacy or security protection if an unauthorized person gains physical access to the device.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Encryption is used in the 21st century to protect digital data and information systems.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] As computing power increased over the years, encryption technology has only become more advanced and secure.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] However, this advancement in technology has also exposed a potential limitation of today's encryption methods.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] The length of the encryption key is an indicator of the strength of the encryption method.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] For example, the original encryption key, DES (Data Encryption Standard), was 56 bits, meaning it had 2^56 combination possibilities.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] With today's computing power, a 56-bit key is no longer secure, being vulnerable to brute force attacks.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Quantum computing uses properties of quantum mechanics in order to process large amounts of data simultaneously.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Quantum computing has been found to achieve computing speeds thousands of times faster than today's supercomputers.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] This computing power presents a challenge to today's encryption technology.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] For example, RSA encryption uses the multiplication of very large prime numbers to create a semiprime number for its public key.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Decoding this key without its private key requires this semiprime number to be factored, which can take a very long time to do with modern computers.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] It would take a supercomputer anywhere between weeks to months to factor in this key.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] However, quantum computing can use quantum algorithms to factor this semiprime number in the same amount of time it takes for normal computers to generate it.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] This would make all data protected by current public-key encryption vulnerable to quantum computing attacks.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Other encryption techniques like elliptic curve cryptography and symmetric key encryption are also vulnerable to quantum computing.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] While quantum computing could be a threat to encryption security in the future, quantum computing as it currently stands is still very limited.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Quantum computing currently is not commercially available, cannot handle large amounts of code, and only exists as computational devices, not computers.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Furthermore, quantum computing advancements will be able to be used in favor of encryption as well.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] The National Security Agency (NSA) is currently preparing post-quantum encryption standards for the future.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Quantum encryption promises a level of security that will be able to counter the threat of quantum computing.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Encryption is an important tool but is not sufficient alone to ensure the security or privacy of sensitive information throughout its lifetime.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Most applications of encryption protect information only at rest or in transit, leaving sensitive data in clear text and potentially vulnerable to improper disclosure during processing, such as by a cloud service for example.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Homomorphic encryption and secure multi-party computation are emerging techniques to compute encrypted data; these techniques are general and Turing complete but incur high computational and/or communication costs.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] In response to encryption of data at rest, cyber-adversaries have developed new types of attacks.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] These more recent threats to encryption of data at rest include cryptographic attacks, stolen ciphertext attacks, attacks on encryption keys, insider attacks, data corruption or integrity attacks, data destruction attacks, and ransomware attacks.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Data fragmentation and active defense data protection technologies attempt to counter some of these attacks, by distributing, moving, or mutating ciphertext so it is more difficult to identify, steal, corrupt, or destroy.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] The question of balancing the need for national security with the right to privacy has been debated for years, since encryption has become critical in today's digital society.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] The modern encryption debate started around the '90s when US government tried to ban cryptography because, according to them, it would threaten national security.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] The debate is polarized around two opposing views.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Those who see strong encryption as a problem making it easier for criminals to hide their illegal acts online and others who argue that encryption keep digital communications safe.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] The debate heated up in 2014, when Big Tech like Apple and Google set encryption by default in their devices.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] This was the start of a series of controversies that puts governments, companies and internet users at stake.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Authenticated encryption algorithms are designed to provide both encryption and integrity protection together.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Standards for cryptographic software and hardware to perform encryption are widely available, but successfully using encryption to ensure security may be a challenging problem.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] A single error in system design or execution can allow successful attacks.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Sometimes an adversary can obtain unencrypted information without directly undoing the encryption.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] See for example traffic analysis, TEMPEST, or Trojan horse.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Encrypting at the time of creation is only secure if the encryption device itself has correct keys and has not been tampered with.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] If an endpoint device has been configured to trust a root certificate that an attacker controls, for example, then the attacker can both inspect and tamper with encrypted data by performing a man-in-the-middle attack anywhere along the message's path.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] The common practice of TLS interception by network operators represents a controlled and institutionally sanctioned form of such an attack, but countries have also attempted to employ such attacks as a form of control and censorship.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Even when encryption effectively conceals a message’s content and prevents tampering, the *length* of the ciphertext remains a form of metadata that can leak sensitive information.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] For instance, the well-known CRIME and BREACH attacks against HTTPS exploited information leakage through encrypted message length as a side-channel attack.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Traffic analysis more broadly refers to techniques that use metadata—such as message size and timing—to infer information about communication patterns.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Applying padding to a message before encryption can help obscure its true plaintext length, though this increases the ciphertext size and adds bandwidth overhead.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Padding may be applied randomly or deterministically, each approach involving different trade-offs.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/encryption] Encrypting and padding data to produce padded uniform random blobs (PURBs) ensures that the ciphertext reveals no metadata about the plaintext’s structure, leaking only asymptotically minimal $O(\log \log M)$ information through its length.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] In cryptography, a **key derivation function** (**KDF**) is a cryptographic algorithm that derives one or more secret keys from a secret value such as a master key, a password, or a passphrase using a pseudorandom function (which typically uses a cryptographic hash function or block cipher).
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] KDFs can be used to stretch keys into longer keys or to obtain keys of a required format, such as converting a group element that is the result of a Diffie–Hellman key exchange into a symmetric key for use with AES.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] Keyed cryptographic hash functions are popular examples of pseudorandom functions used for key derivation.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] The first deliberately slow (key stretching) password-based key derivation function was called "crypt" (or "crypt(3)" after its man page), and was invented by Robert Morris in 1978.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] It would encrypt a constant (zero), using the first 8 characters of the user's password as the key, by performing 25 iterations of a modified DES encryption algorithm (in which a 12-bit number read from the real-time computer clock is used to perturb the calculations).
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] The resulting 64-bit number is encoded as 11 printable characters and then stored in the Unix password file.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] While it was a great advance at the time, increases in processor speeds since the PDP-11 era have made brute-force attacks against crypt feasible, and advances in storage have rendered the 12-bit salt inadequate.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] The crypt function's design also limits the user password to 8 characters, which limits the keyspace and makes strong passphrases impossible.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] Although high throughput is a desirable property in general-purpose hash functions, the opposite is true in password security applications in which defending against brute-force cracking is a primary concern.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] Various algorithms have been designed specifically for this purpose, including bcrypt, scrypt and, more recently, Lyra2 and Argon2 (the latter being the winner of the Password Hashing Competition).
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] The large-scale Ashley Madison data breach in which roughly 36 million passwords hashes were stolen by attackers illustrated the importance of algorithm selection in securing passwords.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) issued a new revision of their digital authentication guidelines, NIST SP 800-63B-3, stating that: "Verifiers SHALL store memorized secrets [i.e. passwords] in a form that is resistant to offline attacks.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] Memorized secrets SHALL be salted and hashed using a suitable one-way key derivation function.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] Key derivation functions take a password, a salt, and a cost factor as inputs then generate a password hash.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] Modern password-based key derivation functions, such as PBKDF2, are based on a recognized cryptographic hash, such as SHA-2, use more salt (at least 64 bits and chosen randomly) and a high iteration count.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] NIST recommends a minimum iteration count of 10,000.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] The original use for a KDF is key derivation, the generation of keys from secret passwords or passphrases.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] Key derivation functions are also used in applications to derive keys from secret passwords or passphrases, which typically do not have the desired properties to be used directly as cryptographic keys.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] In such applications, it is generally recommended that the key derivation function be made deliberately slow so as to frustrate brute-force attack or dictionary attack on the password or passphrase input value.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] Such use may be expressed as DK = KDF(key, salt, iterations), where DK is the derived key, KDF is the key derivation function, key is the original key or password, salt is a random number which acts as cryptographic salt, and iterations refers to the number of iterations of a sub-function.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] The derived key is used instead of the original key or password as the key to the system.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] The values of the salt and the number of iterations (if it is not fixed) are stored with the hashed password or sent as cleartext (unencrypted) with an encrypted message.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] The difficulty of a brute force attack is increased with the number of iterations.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] A practical limit on the iteration count is the unwillingness of users to tolerate a perceptible delay in logging into a computer or seeing a decrypted message.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] The use of salt prevents the attackers from precomputing a dictionary of derived keys.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] An alternative approach, called **key strengthening**, extends the key with a random salt, but then (unlike in key stretching) securely deletes the salt.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] This forces both the attacker and legitimate users to perform a brute-force search for the salt value.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] Although the paper that introduced key stretching referred to this earlier technique and intentionally chose a different name, the term "key strengthening" is now often (arguably incorrectly) used to refer to key stretching.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] Despite their original use for key derivation, KDFs are possibly better known for their use in **password hashing** (password verification by hash comparison), as used by the passwd file or shadow password file.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] Password hash functions should be relatively expensive to calculate in case of brute-force attacks, and KDFs are designed with this characteristic built in.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] The non-secret parameters are called "salt" in this context.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] In 2013 a Password Hashing Competition was announced to choose a new, standard algorithm for password hashing.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] On 20 July 2015 the competition ended and Argon2 was announced as the final winner.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-derivation-function] Four other algorithms received special recognition: Catena, Lyra2, Makwa and yescrypt.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Key management concerns keys at the user level, either between users or systems.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] This is in contrast to key scheduling, which typically refers to the internal handling of keys within the operation of a cipher.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Successful key management is critical to the security of a cryptosystem.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Cryptographic systems may use different types of keys, with some systems using more than one.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] These may include symmetric keys or asymmetric keys.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] In a symmetric key algorithm the keys involved are identical for both encrypting and decrypting a message.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Keys must be chosen carefully, and distributed and stored securely.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Asymmetric keys, also known as public keys, in contrast are two distinct keys that are mathematically linked.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] They are typically used together to communicate.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Public key infrastructure (PKI), the implementation of public key cryptography, requires an organization to establish an infrastructure to create and manage public and private key pairs along with digital certificates.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] The starting point in any certificate and private key management strategy is to create a comprehensive inventory of all certificates, their locations and responsible parties.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] This is not a trivial matter because certificates from a variety of sources are deployed in a variety of locations by different individuals and teams - it's simply not possible to rely on a list from a single certificate authority.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Certificates that are not renewed and replaced before they expire can cause serious downtime and outages.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Once keys are inventoried, key management typically consists of three steps: exchange, storage and use.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Prior to any secured communication, users must set up the details of the cryptography.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] In some instances this may require exchanging identical keys (in the case of a symmetric key system).
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] In others it may require possessing the other party's public key.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] While public keys can be openly exchanged (their corresponding private key is kept secret), symmetric keys must be exchanged over a secure communication channel.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Formerly, exchange of such a key was extremely troublesome, and was greatly eased by access to secure channels such as a diplomatic bag.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Clear text exchange of symmetric keys would enable any interceptor to immediately learn the key, and any encrypted data.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] The advance of public key cryptography in the 1970s has made the exchange of keys less troublesome.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Since the Diffie-Hellman key exchange protocol was published in 1975, it has become possible to exchange a key over an insecure communications channel, which has substantially reduced the risk of key disclosure during distribution.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] It is possible, using something akin to a book code, to include key indicators as clear text attached to an encrypted message.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] The encryption technique used by Richard Sorge's code clerk was of this type, referring to a page in a statistical manual, though it was in fact a code.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] The German Army Enigma symmetric encryption key was a mixed type early in its use; the key was a combination of secretly distributed key schedules and a user chosen session key component for each message.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] In more modern systems, such as OpenPGP compatible systems, a session key for a symmetric key algorithm is distributed encrypted by an asymmetric key algorithm.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] This approach avoids even the necessity for using a key exchange protocol like Diffie-Hellman key exchange.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Another method of key exchange involves encapsulating one key within another.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Typically a master key is generated and exchanged using some secure method.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] This method is usually cumbersome or expensive (breaking a master key into multiple parts and sending each with a trusted courier for example) and not suitable for use on a larger scale.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Once the master key has been securely exchanged, it can then be used to securely exchange subsequent keys with ease.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] This technique is usually termed key wrap.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] A common technique uses block ciphers and cryptographic hash functions.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] A related method is to exchange a master key (sometimes termed a root key) and derive subsidiary keys as needed from that key and some other data (often referred to as diversification data).
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] The most common use for this method is probably in smartcard-based cryptosystems, such as those found in banking cards.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] The bank or credit network embeds their secret key into the card's secure key storage during card production at a secured production facility.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Then at the point of sale the card and card reader are both able to derive a common set of session keys based on the shared secret key and card-specific data (such as the card serial number).
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] This method can also be used when keys must be related to each other (i.e., departmental keys are tied to divisional keys, and individual keys tied to departmental keys).
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] However, tying keys to each other in this way increases the damage which may result from a security breach as attackers will learn something about more than one key.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] This reduces entropy, with regard to an attacker, for each key involved.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] A recent method uses an oblivious pseudorandom function to issue keys without the key management system ever being in a position to see the keys.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] However distributed, keys must be stored securely to maintain communications security.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Security is a big concern and hence there are various techniques in use to do so.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Likely the most common is that an encryption application manages keys for the user and depends on an access password to control use of the key.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Likewise, in the case of smartphone keyless access platforms, they keep all identifying door information off mobile phones and servers and encrypt all data, where just like low-tech keys, users give codes only to those they trust.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] In terms of regulation, there are few that address key storage in depth.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] "Some contain minimal guidance like 'don’t store keys with encrypted data' or suggest that 'keys should be kept securely.'" The notable exceptions to that are PCI DSS 3.2.1, NIST 800-53 and NIST 800–57.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] For optimal security, keys may be stored in a Hardware Security Module (HSM) or protected using technologies such as Trusted Execution Environment (TEE, e.g.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Intel SGX) or Multi-Party Computation (MPC).
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Additional alternatives include utilizing Trusted Platform Modules (TPM), virtual HSMs, aka "Poor Man's Hardware Security Modules" (pmHSM), or non-volatile Field-Programmable-Gate-Arrays (FPGA) with supporting System-on-Chip configurations.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] In order to verify the integrity of a key stored without compromising its actual value a KCV algorithm can be used.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] The major issue is length of time a key is to be used, and therefore frequency of replacement.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Because it increases any attacker's required effort, keys should be frequently changed.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] This also limits loss of information, as the number of stored encrypted messages which will become readable when a key is found will decrease as the frequency of key change increases.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Historically, symmetric keys have been used for long periods in situations in which key exchange was very difficult or only possible intermittently.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Ideally, the symmetric key should change with each message or interaction, so that only that message will become readable if the key is learned (*e.g.*, stolen, cryptanalyzed, or social engineered).
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Security: Vulnerability of keys from outside hackers, malicious insiders.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Availability: Ensuring data accessibility for authorized users.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Heterogeneity: Supporting multiple databases, applications and standards.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Governance: Defining policy-driven access control and protection for data.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Governance includes compliance with data protection requirements.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Key management compliance refers to the oversight, assurance, and capability of being able to demonstrate that keys are securely managed.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Compliance can be achieved with respect to national and international data protection standards and regulations, such as Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard, Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act, Sarbanes–Oxley Act, or General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] A *key management system* (KMS), also known as a *cryptographic key management system* (CKMS) or *enterprise key management system* (EKMS), is an integrated approach for generating, distributing and managing cryptographic keys for devices and applications.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] They may cover all aspects of security - from the secure generation of keys over the secure exchange of keys up to secure key handling and storage on the client.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Thus, a KMS includes the backend functionality for key generation, distribution, and replacement as well as the client functionality for injecting keys, storing and managing keys on devices.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Many specific applications have developed their own key management systems with home grown protocols.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] However, as systems become more interconnected keys need to be shared between those different systems.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] To facilitate this, key management standards have evolved to define the protocols used to manage and exchange cryptographic keys and related information.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] KMIP is an extensible key management protocol that has been developed by many organizations working within the OASIS standards body.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] The first version was released in 2010, and it has been further developed by an active technical committee.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] The protocol allows for the creation of keys and their distribution among disparate software systems that need to utilize them.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] It covers the full key life cycle of both symmetric and asymmetric keys in a variety of formats, the wrapping of keys, provisioning schemes, and cryptographic operations as well as meta data associated with the keys.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] The protocol is backed by an extensive series of test cases, and interoperability testing is performed between compliant systems each year.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] A list of some 80 products that conform to the KMIP standard can be found on the OASIS website.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] The security policy of a key management system provides the rules that are to be used to protect keys and metadata that the key management system supports.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] This protection covers the complete key life-cycle from the time the key becomes operational to its elimination.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] A public-key infrastructure is a type of key management system that uses hierarchical digital certificates to provide authentication, and public keys to provide encryption.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] PKIs are used in World Wide Web traffic, commonly in the form of SSL and TLS.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Group key management means managing the keys in a group communication.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Most of the group communications use multicast communication so that if the message is sent once by the sender, it will be received by all the users.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] The main problem in multicast group communication is its security.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] In order to improve the security, various keys are given to the users.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] Using the keys, the users can encrypt their messages and send them secretly.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-management] IETF.org released RFC 4046, entitled Multicast Security (MSEC) Group Key Management Architecture, which discusses the challenges of group key management.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-wrap] In cryptography, **key wrap** constructions are a class of symmetric encryption algorithms designed to encapsulate (encrypt) cryptographic key material.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-wrap] The Key Wrap algorithms are intended for applications such as protecting keys while in untrusted storage or transmitting keys over untrusted communications networks.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-wrap] The constructions are typically built from standard primitives such as block ciphers and cryptographic hash functions.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-wrap] Key Wrap may be considered as a form of key encapsulation algorithm, although it should not be confused with the more commonly known *asymmetric* (public-key) key encapsulation algorithms (e.g., PSEC-KEM).
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-wrap] Key Wrap algorithms can be used in a similar application: to securely transport a session key by encrypting it under a long-term encryption key.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-wrap] In the late 1990s, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) posed the "Key Wrap" problem: to develop secure and efficient cipher-based key encryption algorithms.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-wrap] The resulting algorithms would be formally evaluated by NIST, and eventually approved for use in NIST-certified cryptographic modules.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-wrap] NIST did not precisely define the security goals of the resulting algorithm, and left further refinement to the algorithm developers.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-wrap] Goals (3) and (5) are particularly important, given that many widely deployed authenticated encryption algorithms (e.g., AES-CCM) are already sufficient to accomplish the remaining goals.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-wrap] Several constructions have been proposed.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-wrap] Each of the proposed algorithms can be considered as a form of authenticated encryption algorithm providing confidentiality for highly entropic messages such as cryptographic keys.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-wrap] The AES Key Wrap Specification, AESKW, TDKW, and AKW1 are intended to maintain confidentiality under adaptive chosen ciphertext attacks, while the AKW2 algorithm is designed to be secure only under known-plaintext (or weaker) attacks.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-wrap] (The stated goal of AKW2 is for use in legacy systems and computationally limited devices where use of the other algorithms would be impractical.) AESKW, TDKW and AKW2 also provide the ability to authenticate cleartext "header", an associated block of data that is not encrypted.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-wrap] Rogaway and Shrimpton evaluated the design of the ANSX9.102 algorithms with respect to the stated security goals.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-wrap] Among their general findings, they noted the lack of clearly stated design goals for the algorithms, and the absence of security proofs for all constructions.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-wrap] In their paper, Rogaway and Shrimpton proposed a provable key-wrapping algorithm (SIV—the Synthetic Initialization Vector mode) that authenticates and encrypts an arbitrary string and authenticates, but does not encrypt, associated data which can be bound into the wrapped key.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/key-wrap] This has been specified as a new AES mode in RFC 5297.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] Symmetric-key encryption can use either stream ciphers or block ciphers.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] Stream ciphers encrypt the digits (typically bytes), or letters (in substitution ciphers) of a message one at a time.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] Substitution ciphers are well-known ciphers, but can be easily decrypted using a frequency table.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] Block ciphers take a number of bits and encrypt them in a single unit, padding the plaintext to achieve a multiple of the block size.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] The Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) algorithm, approved by NIST in December 2001, uses 128-bit blocks.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] Examples of popular symmetric-key algorithms include Twofish, Serpent, AES (Rijndael), Camellia, Salsa20, ChaCha20, Blowfish, CAST5, Kuznyechik, RC4, DES, 3DES, Skipjack, Safer, and IDEA.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] Symmetric ciphers are commonly used to achieve other cryptographic primitives than just encryption.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] Encrypting a message does not guarantee that it will remain unchanged while encrypted.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] Hence, often a message authentication code is added to a ciphertext to ensure that changes to the ciphertext will be noted by the receiver.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] Message authentication codes can be constructed from an AEAD cipher (e.g.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] However, symmetric ciphers cannot be used for non-repudiation purposes except by involving additional parties.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] Another application is to build hash functions from block ciphers.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] See one-way compression function for descriptions of several such methods.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] Many modern block ciphers are based on a construction proposed by Horst Feistel.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] Feistel's construction makes it possible to build invertible functions from other functions that are themselves not invertible.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] Symmetric ciphers have historically been susceptible to known-plaintext attacks, chosen-plaintext attacks, differential cryptanalysis and linear cryptanalysis.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] Careful construction of the functions for each round can greatly reduce the chances of a successful attack.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] It is also possible to increase the key length or the rounds in the encryption process to better protect against attack.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] This, however, tends to increase the processing power and decrease the speed at which the process runs due to the amount of operations the system needs to do.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] Most modern symmetric-key algorithms appear to be resistant to the threat of post-quantum cryptography.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] Quantum computers would exponentially increase the speed at which these ciphers can be decoded; notably, Grover's algorithm would take the square-root of the time traditionally required for a brute-force attack, although these vulnerabilities can be compensated for by doubling key length.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] For example, a 128 bit AES cipher would not be secure against such an attack as it would reduce the time required to test all possible iterations from over 10 quintillion years to about six months.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] By contrast, it would still take a quantum computer the same amount of time to decode a 256 bit AES cipher as it would a conventional computer to decode a 128 bit AES cipher.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] For this reason, AES-256 is believed to be "quantum resistant".
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] Symmetric-key algorithms require both the sender and the recipient of a message to have the same secret key.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] All early cryptographic systems required either the sender or the recipient to somehow receive a copy of that secret key over a physically secure channel.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] When used with asymmetric ciphers for key transfer, pseudorandom key generators are nearly always used to generate the symmetric cipher session keys.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] However, lack of randomness in those generators or in their initialization vectors is disastrous and has led to cryptanalytic breaks in the past.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] Therefore, it is essential that an implementation use a source of high entropy for its initialization.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] A reciprocal cipher is a cipher where, just as one enters the plaintext into the cryptography system to get the ciphertext, one could enter the ciphertext into the same place in the system to get the plaintext.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] A reciprocal cipher is also sometimes referred as **self-reciprocal cipher**.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] Practically all mechanical cipher machines implement a reciprocal cipher, a mathematical involution on each typed-in letter.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] Instead of designing two kinds of machines, one for encrypting and one for decrypting, all the machines can be identical and can be set up (keyed) the same way.
[src:envelope-encryption-deep/symmetric-key-algorithm] The majority of all modern ciphers can be classified as either a stream cipher, most of which use a reciprocal XOR cipher combiner, or a block cipher, most of which use a Feistel cipher or Lai–Massey scheme with a reciprocal transformation in each round.
